intshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Cyllyn Ap Blaidd was born in 0993, in Dolbenmaen, Caernarfonshire, Wales, his father, Lord Merion Blaidd ap Hywel Dda, was 25 and his mother, Blaidd ap Hywed of Gest, was 21. He married Hynydd verch Rhys about 1023, in Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1028, in Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"0993–1028":"0993–1028","1000–1036":"1000–1036","0997–Female":"0997–Surnud","1025–1089":"1025–1089","0968–0993":"0968–0993","0972–Female":"0972–Surnud","1000":"1000","0997":"0997","1028":"1028","992":"0992","0972":"0972","993":"0993","0993":"0993","1025":"1025","1036":"1036","Abt 1023":"umbes 1023","ABT 1024":"umbes 1024","1089":"1089","about 1025":"umbes 1025","0968":"0968","Dolbenmaen, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Dolbenmaen, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Gest, Dolbenmaen, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Dolbenmaen, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Gest Near Penmorga, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","(Wales-Powys)":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales"},"fi":{"0993–1028":"0993–1028","1000–1036":"1000–1036","0997–Female":"0997–Kuollut","1025–1089":"1025–1089","0968–0993":"0968–0993","0972–Female":"0972–Kuollut","1000":"1000","0997":"0997","1028":"1028","992":"0992","0972":"0972","993":"0993","0993":"0993","1025":"1025","1036":"1036","Abt 1023":"noin 1023","ABT 1024":"noin 1024","1089":"1089","about 1025":"noin 1025","0968":"0968","Dolbenmaen, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Dolbenmaen, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gest,